  "prompt": "What happens if petrol is used in a diesel engine?",
  "response": "If petrol is mistakenly used in a diesel engine, several serious problems can occur:\n\n1. Immediate consequences:\n- Fuel system damage\n- Lubrication failure\n- Increased friction between engine components\n- Potential engine seizure\n\n2. Specific technical issues:\n- Petrol lacks the lubricating properties of diesel\n- Diesel engines rely on compression for ignition, while petrol requires spark\n- Higher volatility of petrol can cause premature ignition\n- Risk of significant internal engine damage\n\n3. Potential damage:\n- Scoring of cylinder walls\n- Piston and connecting rod damage\n- Fuel pump failure\n- Potential complete engine breakdown\n\n4. Recommended actions:\n- Do NOT start the engine\n- Do NOT drive the vehicle\n- Drain the fuel system completely\n- Have a professional mechanic inspect and potentially repair the engine\n- Possible replacement of fuel pump, injectors, and other components\n\n5. Repair costs:\n- Can range from hundreds to thousands of dollars\n- May require partial or complete engine replacement in severe cases\n\nThe key is to avoid using petrol in a diesel engine and immediately seek professional help if such a mistake occurs.",
